fields.remarks: The fuga is based on an ID I have already asserted in another comment. It is hard to find any other structural element in this fuga, as it is quite free. The first kyrie is based on only one element, leading to the CAD.

There are two ways to interpret this relationship. The first one is to consider that Sohier has amplified the first Fg in order to make his first Kyrie. The second one is to consider he has seen 'Vidi speciosam'and 'cuius inaestimabilis'as one and the same Fg, broken by another soggetto ('de super rivos aquarum') that he has decided to omit in his missa.

The position of the clausules (tenorizans, cantizans and bassus) is the same, and the two other voices behave with a delay that is quite comparable, which makes me think Sohier could have reproduced this CAD to finish his first Kyrie. I would not take any bet on this assertion, the model is not clearly structured - at least is very complex in its structure -, so it would not surprise me from Sohier to pick materials here and there in order to build his missa like a LEGO game...

In the second duo, the first entry has been anticipated, so that the counterpoint is the one of an ID, even though the time interval of entries is not 'regular'. The Primis Tenor enters in imitation, turning the ID into a Fg.
The 'change of voice role prevents me from asserting a quotation with monnayage, even though the time intervals and the notes are the same.

This assertion is interesting on the point point of view of form. If we take into account that Sohier started his Christe on the material of 'Quae est ista quae proces sit', the second part of the model, we can assume that the first Kyrie quotes the whole first part of the song. 'Vidi speciosam'and 'cuius inaestimabilis'are built on the same soggetto, which start on a fifth can be considered to be found back in the cadential 'et lilia con valium'. Between these three sentences, several soggetti  have been omited by Sohier: 'ascendentem...', 'de super rivos', 'et sicut dies', circumdabant'. I assert a New combination, for I assume Sohier has taken three sentences and made them into one. We could also think, taking the omission into consideration, that the sentences of the model are just one big fuga, broken by some new soggetti, and that this fuga has been transformed with amplification and change of voice role.

The countersubject to the chant soggetto is slightly flexed after its fourth note: either B-C-G or B-G. After the second NIm presentation the countersubject is brought into fuga with itself, though these entrances are incomplete. There is a suggestion of periodicity in the regular entrances of the countersubject every four breves.

These are 4-voice NIMs, in which the ornamented chant melody provides one subject. The second presentation is rotated (invertible counterpoint): countersubject three, which was in the bassus in the first presentation, is now moved up an octave into the contratenor. There is a brief suggestion of fuga on countersubject 2 in the first three notes of the quinta vox in b. 14.
Chant melody embellished with final cantizans cadence and combined with 3 countersubjects to form 4-voice NIMs.

Chant melody provides one of the two soggettos for three overlapping two-voice NIMs. The simple cadence in the chant (A-G-F-G-G) is embellished with a leap up of a third followed by a descent to an under-third cantizans figure (A-C-B-A-G-G-F#-E-G).
The first entrance of the ornamented chant soggetto is "flexed" only to the extent that it is missing its tail motive; otherwise the entries are all intervallically and rhythmically strict.
The simple cadence formula of the chant (-G-A-G) is embellished by interpolating a more active descending-fourth motive (C-B-A-G)

Josquin interpolated this falling-fourth scale motive into the chant soggetto, and formed it both into fuga (in two different interlocks) as well as shadowing it in sixths (quinta vox/bassus, bb. 41-42) and thirds (tenor/sexta vox, bb. 44-45)

This motive could be seen as new material interpolated into the chant preceding the A-G descent on "maris", or as a foreshadowing/borrowing of the following chant segment ("stella vocaris") - perhaps a musical device suggested by the "maris/vocaris" rhyme?

The lower three voices accompanying this fuga draw freely on the stretto fuga interval stock of (predominantly) falling fourths and rising thirds, without forming a clearly repeating pattern or formal countersubject

This is really an MTI presentation. Josquin brings in fuga entrances of the chant-derived descending-fourth motive alternately at 2-sb and 1-sb time intervals. As a result, the lattice of entrances involves *two* different repeated imitative duos, both altered  through ic12. Entrances separated by 2sb are at 8+ and 5-; entrances separated by 1sb are at 4- and 9+.

Josquin ornaments the chant melody's simple scalar descent of a fourth (C-B-A-G) by introducing an extra G (C-B-G-A-G). This seems to be a standard way of ornamenting this scalar motive, also used by other composers treating the same chant melody (?)
Direct (quasi-ostinato) repetition of a cadential module in the same two voices.

My initial impression was that Josquin uses only the chant melody for "fieres et" in this section, omitting the following segment on "et ipse frater" - but maybe one could argue that the chant melody is still present in the bass, in highly ornamented/disguised form. Is it significant that the Josquin also has different text here? (frater vs. Pater)

The upper four voices form a lattice of invertible periodic entrances, with a repeating pattern of relationships creating two repetitions corresponding to the motivic repetition within the chant melody. The lower two voices form two NIms with the subject, only one of which is notated here.
The descending-fourth motive in the chant is embellished in the same way as previously at "Te Deus pater"

This is the second of two NIms formed by the chant subject (in periodic entrances in the upper four voices) and a countersubject in one of the two lowest voices. (See the other relationship for a description of the PEn and the first NIm).

Here Josquin breaks the chant phrase into two motives, one corresponding to "et mittens" and the other to "sic salutavit". The "et mittens" motive forms a non-imitative duo which is repeated almost immediately by the same voices at the same pitch; the countersubject of this non-imitative duo is shared with the *other* non-imitative cell, as indicated here by the "fuga" entry. See the other relationship for details of the second non-imitative cell.

The chant motive provides one strand of a homorhythmic four-voice NIm, which becomes a five-voice NIm when repeated through the addition of a fifth strand in the discantus. There is a limited amount of invertible counterpoint in that the chant motive which was in the bassus (but not the lowest voice) is moved up an octave into the contratenor for the second two presentations.

Josquin flexes the chant soggetto between its second and third notes (A-B-A-G-.. becomes B-C-A-G-..). Very loose suggestion of fuga entry in the bass. There is a stretto-fuga-derived sequence of rising fourths and falling thirds in the tenor and sexta vox.

This is a *3-voice* NIm with *4* different motives. For the purposes of this relationship only the portion of the chant soggetto that participates in the NIm is shown, although in both cases it is part of a longer fuga entrances. Motive 1 (A-G-F) comes from the chant at "-gris medi-"; motive 2 (G-F-E-C-D) is always heard in one of the bass voices, followed by tenorizans or basizans motion; motive 3 (A-B-C-A) is usually heard in an inner voice; motive 4 is a decorated cantizans cadence. We hear two different three-voice combinations of these four motives in alteration: first 1+2+3, then 2+3+4, then repeat. In other words, motives 2+3 are heard each time, in combination either with the soggetto (motive 1) or with the cantizans cadence (motive 4)

The material Willaert borrowed from b. 55 is part of a NIm in Josquin, not noted here because the other subject is not borrowed.

Every movement of the Willaert piece is structured as a double canon for [discantus], [contratenor primus], tenor and bassus (in some order).  Since the time and pitch interval between the first and second pairs of voices is always the same, every section consists of overlapping ID presentations. Only the portion of the ID which also participates in the NIm is selected here.

The soggetto with which the double canon begins is taken from Josquin's opening PEn. Its first two canonic entrances are combined with a countersubject in the free voices, whose first five notes are taken from Josquin's seventh point of imitation ("preces nostras")

This duo begins imitatively with entrances of a 3-note head motive, followed by differing continuations; the continuation of the upper/leading entrance in Josquin's duos is not borrowed and is not indicated here.

The IDs arise as a consequence of the double-canon structure; only the portion involving borrowed material is highlighted here. The borrowed soggetto divides into two motives (A-Bb-A and A-G-A-Bb-A), which Willaert brings back at the conclusion of the canonic phrase in the upper voices. Their overlapping with the repetition of the opening duo in the lower voices results in additional fuga and NIms where the four voices overlap in bb. 40--48
Willaert transforms one voice of Josquin's non-imitative duo into fuga (and later into different non-imitative duos)
This is one voice of a NIm in Josquin's motet; the other subject is not selected as it is not borrowed here (it was used on its own as a countersubject in Willaert's first point of imitation).
This segment of the double canon is heard only once (it is not repeated by the lower voices) due to its proximity to the final cadence of the section.

This portion of Willaert's double canon arguably quotes (in twofold augmentation) one of the two soggetti from Josquin's setting of "Preces nostras", although the motive in question is sufficiently generic that this is arguable. The other subject from this section of the Josquin was already used in the first point of imitation.

The subject ends with a cantizans cadence, the countersubject with a tenorizans cadence. Josquin first presents the subject and countersubject as singletons, then in NIm combination. Two more presentations of the NIm flex the subject and retain only the tail of the countersubject (it is joined to a new head-motive, not borrowed and so not indicated here).

fields.remarks: It is difficult to decide whether this passage of fuga from Morales derives from Josquin, Pieton, both, or neither. All three composers wrote a passage of complex fuga on this subject, and given the restrictions of counterpoint they would inevitably have arrived at similar combinations. On the other hand, Josquin also uses an interlock at M2,4- (congruent to 11-); in addition, Morales and Josquin both feature interlocks with time interval M4 and pitch intervals 8+ and 4+/5-. Morales's version of this chant most closely matches Pieton's, although the treatment is generic enough that this could be coincidence. Interestingly, Pieton does *not* treat this melodic line as a self-contained unit: in his setting, the first three notes (A-B-G-) belong to one imitative motive and the last three (-E-F-G) to a different one.

This three-note "cumulative fourth" motive is fairly generic, and the relationship to a completely different segment of the chant than the surrounding ones may seem far-fetched. However, there *is* a later section of this mass movement apparently based on a more extensive extract from the same section of the chant (bb. 91-115), and the brief introduction of the motive here could be understood as "foreshadowing". Alternatively, this motive could also be understood as the melodic inversion of the chant motive that follows in bb. 22-8.

Morales seems to have taken a motive from Josquin's contrapuntal duo, re-spliced the first two notes (turning a rising third into a rising second), and formed it into fuga which simultaneously forms NIms with the chant soggetto. On purely musical grounds this might seem a relatively weak relationship, since the motives involved are generic. What is interesting are the resonances between the texts: Josquin's motive sets the text "quo salvantur omnia", and it is placed in counterpoint with a chant subject originally setting "et ex te verbum incarnatum" to set the new Credo text "et homo factus est". fields.remarks: This is a fairly intricate borrowing. Josquin's original consists of a repeated NIm. Both subjects of the NIm begin with a common head-motive, X, so the upper voice's subject can be symbolised as XY and the lower voice's as XZ. Willaert's canonic subject then has the structure YXZ(N)XZ, with (N) symbolizing new material. The first two canonic entrances produce an ID in which YXZ combines in fuga with itself, a new combination not heard in Josquin; this is, of course, repeated exactly by the later two canonic entrances. In addition, Willaert introduces additional entrances of motive Z in the free voices of bb. 138ff., replicating the latter half of Josquin's NIm (Y+Z). Finally, Willaert also contrives the canon so that the XZ tail of the first two canonic entrances overlaps with the Y motive at the beginning of the later two canonic entrances, producing two more presentations of the (Y+Z) NIm. Two notes of Josquin's motive Y are omitted from Willaert (A-A-Bb replaces F-G-A-Bb), and the joint between motives X and Z is altered. Willaert's first two NIm presentations have the subjects moved an octave closer together compared to Josquin, but the latter two presentations have them in their original relationship.

These head-motives are followed by longer continuations which, in canon, form an extended ID; they are analysed simply as fuga here since there is no substantial overlap between each entrance of the common head motive.
